Series 1
| ShortSummary=After the withdrawal of the Roman Empire from Britain, the Anglo-Saxons become the next conquerors and eventually begin the creation of England.
| LineColor=3F6136
}}
| ShortSummary=The rise of the Anglo-Saxons, the wars against the Vikings and the victory over King Harold by the Norman Duke William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings.
| LineColor=3F6136
}}
| ShortSummary=Following the Battle of Hastings and subsequent Norman Conquest. This covers a tumultuous time in English history, which saw murders and eventually, civil war.  The story of all of the English monarchs of the House of Normandy.
| LineColor=3F6136
}}
| ShortSummary=The reign of the Angevins Henry II of England, and his conflict with the Archbishop of Canterbury, Thomas Becket, the corrupted reign of King John and the long struggled reign of Henry III.
| LineColor=3F6136
}}
| ShortSummary=The reigns of three Edwards: Edward I, and his attempt at a United Kingdom, how his son Edward II almost lost it all, but restored by Edward III, grandson of Edward I.
| LineColor=3F6136
}}
| ShortSummary=Follows the reigns made famous by Shakespeare: Richard II, Henry IV, Henry V and Henry VI. A time of civil unrest and doubt in monarchy itself.
| LineColor=3F6136
}}
}}
Series 2
| ShortSummary=The Wars of the Roses and the birth of the Tudors.
| LineColor=000080
}}
| ShortSummary=The reign of Henry VIII, his divorces and resulting dissociation with Rome, which led to the Dissolution of the Monasteries.
| LineColor=000080
}}
| ShortSummary=Following the death of Henry VIII and the Act of Succession of 1543, which allowed all three of his children to rule. Edward VI, Mary I and Elizabeth I.
| LineColor=000080
}}
| ShortSummary=With the defeat of the Spanish Armada, the English royalty was at its zenith. Scotland and England became united under the Stuart King James I (VI of Scotland), but his son Charles I within a generation would throw the country into civil war.
| LineColor=000080
}}
| ShortSummary=1644, the English Civil War was at its height and monarchy - indisputable before the war - was under threat.
| LineColor=000080
}}
}}
Series 3
| ShortSummary=Starting in 1660 with the return from exile of King Charles II. By aligning his throne with Catholic France and Protestant Parliament, Charles's reign restored the authority of the English crown and laid the foundation of the world's first modern state.
| LineColor=800080
}}
| ShortSummary=Looking at the "Bloodless Revolution" of 1688, the Parliament-devised plot to overthrow England's last Roman Catholic King, James II, and replace him with his Dutch Protestant son-in-law William of Orange.
| LineColor=800080
}}
| ShortSummary=In just 25 years after the Glorious Revolution of 1688, England was transformed from an insignificant minor state to become part of the greatest power in Europe: Great Britain.
| LineColor=800080
}}
| ShortSummary=In 1714, an obscure German Prince was crowned King George I of Great Britain, signalling the beginning of a new political era that saw the rise of the new role of the Prime Minister, and established the pattern of political modernity we are familiar with today.
| LineColor=800080
}}
| ShortSummary=When, in 1789, the Bastille prison in Paris was stormed and the French Revolution began, few in Britain - least of all King George III, who was recovering from one of his bouts of madness - thought that it would lead to a cataclysmic war with France.
| LineColor=800080
}}
}}
Series 4
| ShortSummary=Death of Queen Victoria, to present day. Speculation on the path of King Charles III or King George VII.
| LineColor=FF6048
}}
}}
